properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 9:53 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. This line of severe thunderstorms is currently located from near Moose Jaw to Dilke to Tisdale and is tracking to the northeast at 20 km/h. Very heavy rainfall in excess of 50 mm per hour is likely with this line of thunderstorms. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong wind gusts that may cause damage are expected or occurring. In Resolute southeasterly winds will continue to strengthen tonight with gusts of 90 km/h starting overnight tonight. Winds will diminish Friday evening. In Grise Fiord easterly wind gusts are expected to reach, or possibly exceed, 100 km/h. Strong winds are expected to develop overnight and diminish Friday night. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

Description: At 8:02 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a line of dangerous thunderstorms capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to golf ball size hail and heavy rain. This line of severe thunderstorms is currently located from Wood Mountain to Mortlach to Davidson to Humboldt and is tracking to the northeast at 20 km/h. Golf ball sized hail was recently reported near Parkbeg. Very heavy rainfall in excess of 50 mm per hour is likely with this line of thunderstorms. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. A trough of low pressure continues to support scattered thunderstorms over western Saskatchewan this afternoon. The threat for severe thunderstorms will shift eastwards this afternoon, where further development is expected. These thunderstorms will likely persist well into the evening and overnight hours bringing a threat for hail to the size of loonies and locally heavy rainfall in excess of 50 millimeters. This severe thunderstorm watch may be expanded eastwards later this evening as the event progresses. ### Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2019-08-23T07:52:18-00:00
